<h2>A Rule and a Way of Life</h2>
<p>Jesus, the night before he died, prayed one prayer for all his people — that we would be one. Not someday. Not metaphorically. One.</p>

<p>At Christ the Reconciler, everything we do is a response to that prayer. Over time, that response has taken two concrete shapes: a rule and a way of life.</p>

<p>Both flow from John 17. Both are for anyone who wants to take Jesus' prayer seriously — whether you live here, follow from a distance, or are just beginning to explore.</p>

<h3>The Rule: A Statement of Personal Devotion</h3>
<p>A rule of life is an ancient practice — a structured set of commitments that keeps you accountable to what you say you believe, and shapes how you actually treat people.</p>

<p>The Statement of Personal Devotion is CTR's rule. It is a personal covenant, made freely, by individuals who want to concretely live out John 17 in their own lives.</p>

<p>It includes five renunciations — things you leave behind — and five commitments — things you take up. Together they describe what it looks like, in practice, to be a person genuinely pursuing the unity Jesus prayed for. These are not aspirations. They are actions.</p>

<p>You don't have to live in Elgin to make this commitment. You don't have to be part of our residential community. The Statement is for anyone — wherever you are, whatever tradition you come from — who wants to say yes to John 17.</p>

<a href="#">Read the Statement of Personal Devotion</a>
<a href="#">Learn about making or renewing the commitment</a>

<h3>The Way of Life: Five Practices</h3>
<p>A way of life is less formal than a rule — it is a set of rhythms, habits, and orientations that shape you over time without requiring a formal commitment. You grow into a way of life. You practice it imperfectly. You return to it when you've drifted.</p>

<p>CTR's way of life is organized around five practices. These are not a program or a curriculum. They are the outward expression of what it looks like to be a community — and a person — shaped by John 17.</p>

<h4>Prayer</h4>
<p>We pray daily, together and apart, for the unity of the Body of Christ. The Bridge Prayer is the heartbeat of this practice — a short daily liturgy that joins us to Christians across traditions and around the world.</p>

<h4>Reconciliation</h4>
<p>Reconciliation is not a feeling. It is a concrete set of actions that removes hostility, repairs damage, and restores relationship. We practice it with each other. We teach others how.</p>

<h4>Formation</h4>
<p>We are shaped by scripture, by teaching, and by the long tradition of the church. Formation is the practice of letting yourself be changed — by what you read, what you hear, and who you do life with.</p>

<h4>Hospitality</h4>
<p>Our door is open. Hospitality is the practice of welcoming the stranger, sharing the table, and making room — for guests, for retreatants, for anyone who wants to come closer.</p>

<h4>Work</h4>
<p>Life together requires real work. Cooking, building, gardening, administration — work is not a distraction from our mission. It is part of it. The practice of work is the practice of showing up, faithfully, for what needs to be done.</p>

